(316, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;Which Halogen Is A Gas At Room Temperature And Is Pale Yellow In Color?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'Chlorine (Cl) ', 'Fluorine (F)', 'Â Iodine (I)', 'Bromine (Br)', '', 'B Explanation Fluorine is a halogen that is a gas at room temperature and is pale yellow in color. Halogens are a group in the periodic table consisting of five chemically related elements: fluorine (F), chlorine (Cl), bromine (Br), iodine (I), and astati', 0, '2024-02-22 12:14:00'),
(317, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;What Unit Of Temperature Should Be Used When Applying The Ideal Gas Law?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'Â Fahrenheit (Â°F) ', 'Kelvin (K) ', 'Rankine (Â°R)', 'Celsius (Â°C)', '', 'B Explanation Temperature must be expressed in Kelvin when using the ideal gas law. The Kelvin scale is an absolute temperature scale, and its zero point (0 K) corresponds to absolute zero, the point at which the kinetic energy of gas particles is minimal', 0, '2024-02-22 12:15:33'),
(318, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;Chlorine Gas Is Commonly Used In The Production Of Which Of The Following Industrial Compounds?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) ', 'Â Methane', 'Ammonia ', 'Ethanol', '', 'A Explanation Chlorine gas is used in the production of chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), which were once widely used as refrigerants, aerosol propellants, and foam-blowing agents. However, due to their harmful impact on the ozone layer, their use has been sign', 0, '2024-02-22 12:16:58'),
(319, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;The Process Of Rusting Is An Example Of The Formation Of&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'Basic oxide ', 'Acidic Oxide', 'Reducing Oxide', 'Amphoteric Oxide', '', 'A Explanation Rusting is the corrosion of iron or steel due to exposure to oxygen and moisture in the air, resulting in the formation of iron oxide (Fe2 O3  or Fe3 O4 ), which is an example of an acidic oxide.   ', 0, '2024-02-22 12:18:14'),
(320, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;Which Of The Following Is An Example Of A Primary Cell?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'Alkaline battery B.Â C. D.', 'Nickel-Cadmium Battery ', 'Â Lead-Acid Battery', 'Â Lithium-Ion Battery', '', 'A Explanation Primary cells are non-rechargeable batteries, and the alkaline battery is a common example of a primary cell   ', 0, '2024-02-22 12:19:31'),
(321, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;Which Of The Following Is A Characteristic Property Of Acids?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'Turn litmus paper blue ', 'Â Bitter Taste', 'Â PH Value Above 7 ', 'React With Metals To Produce Hydrogen Gas', '', ' D Explanation Acids are substances that can donate protons (H+) in aqueous solutions. When acids react with certain metals, they can release hydrogen gas (H2) as one of the products. This is a common behavior of many acids and can be used to distinguish ', 0, '2024-02-22 12:20:59'),
(322, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;The Lanthanides And Actinides Are Located In Which Block Of The Periodic Table?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'P-block ', 'S-Block', 'Â F-Block', 'D-Block', '', 'C Explanation The lanthanides and actinides are located in the f-block of the periodic table, which is a separate row placed at the bottom of the main table. These elements are also known as the inner transition metals.', 0, '2024-02-22 12:22:35'),
(323, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;What Is The IUPAC Name For The Compound CCl44?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'Tetrahydrochloride ', 'Tetrachloromethane', 'Â Carbon Tetrachloride', 'Chloroform', '', 'B Explanation The compound CCl4  is a chlorinated hydrocarbon with a central carbon atom and four chlorine atoms attached to it. According to IUPAC rules, the correct name for this compound is &quot;tetrachloromethane.&quot;', 0, '2024-02-22 12:24:10'),
(324, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;Which Of The Following Statements Is True Regarding The Melting And Boiling Points Of Pure Substances?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'The boiling point is always higher than the melting point', 'The Melting Point Is Always Higher Than The Boiling Point', 'The Melting And Boiling Points Are Always The Same For All Substances', 'The Melting And Boiling Points Can Vary Depending On The Substance', '', 'D Explanation The melting and boiling points are specific physical properties of each substance and can vary depending on the nature of the substance. Different substances have different melting and boiling points, which are determined by the strength of ', 0, '2024-02-22 12:25:56'),
(325, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;An Element Has An Atomic Number Of 8 And A Mass Number Of 16. How Many Neutrons Does This Element Have?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '24 ', '16 ', '8 ', '32', '', 'C Explanation The atomic number of an element is equal to the number of protons, which in this case is 8. The mass number is the total number of protons and neutrons, which is 16. To find the number of neutrons, we subtract the atomic number from the mass', 0, '2024-02-22 12:27:49'),
(326, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;Which Of The Following Statements Is True For Strong Electrolytes?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'They do not conduct electricity in the molten state ', 'They Completely Dissociate Into Ions In Solution ', 'They Are Non-Polar Substances', 'They Partially Dissociate Into Ions In Solution', '', 'B Explanation They completely dissociate into ions in solution. Strong electrolytes are substances that fully dissociate into ions when dissolved in water or melted. As a result, they produce a high concentration of ions in the solution, allowing for effi', 0, '2024-02-22 12:29:57'),
(327, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;What Is The Maximum Number Of Electrons That Can Occupy The Second Energy Level (n=2)?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', '2 electrons ', '18 Electrons ', '8 Electrons ', '32 Electrons', '', ' C Explanation The correct answer is (b). The second energy level (n=2) can hold a maximum of 8 electrons. It consists of two subshells, 2s and 2p, which can hold 2 and 6 electrons, respectively.   ', 0, '2024-02-22 12:31:35'),
(328, 17, 'JAMB', 'CHEMISTRY', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;Which Of The Following Is A Common Laboratory Indicator For Bases?&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'Methyl orange', 'Â Phenolphthalein', 'Bromothymol Blue', 'Litmus', '', 'B Explanation Phenolphthalein is a common laboratory indicator used to detect the presence of bases in a solution. In its basic form (pH &gt; 8.3), it turns pink or purple, indicating the presence of a base.', 0, '2024-02-22 12:33:29'),
(329, 17, 'JAMB', 'PHYSICS', '2023', '&lt;p&gt;&lt;img Src=&quot;https://myschool.ng/storage/classroom/EgkSSs56LKmhXTOSnQuvwd2zNIGTuGhSiOrwmMvt.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;p&gt;The Property Of Wave Shown In The Diagram Above Is?&lt;br /&gt;\r\n&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\r\n', 'Diffraction ', 'Refraction ', 'Polarisation ', 'Interference', '', 'A Explanation Diffraction is the bending of waves around the corners of an obstacle or through an aperture.', 0, '2024-02-23 09:32:08'),
